======================================================================
PART 1: THE FUNDAMENTAL RECURRENCE z² = 5z - 6
======================================================================

  z² - 5z + 6 = (z-2)(z-3) = 0

  The general solution: a(n) = A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ

  Special sequences:
  a(n) = 2ⁿ:     1, 2, 4,  8, 16,  32,  64, 128, 256, 512, 1024 ...
  a(n) = 3ⁿ:     1, 3, 9, 27, 81, 243, 729 ...
  a(n) = 3ⁿ-2ⁿ:  0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665 ...
  a(n) = 2·3ⁿ-2ⁿ: 1, 4, 14, 46, 146, 454 ... (sum 3^k+2^k?)

  2^n: [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128]... satisfies z²=5z-6? True
  3^n: [1, 3, 9, 27, 81, 243, 729, 2187]... satisfies z²=5z-6? True
  3^n-2^n: [0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059]... satisfies z²=5z-6? True
  5^n: [1, 5, 25, 125, 625, 3125, 15625, 78125]... satisfies z²=5z-6? False
  6^n: [1, 6, 36, 216, 1296, 7776, 46656, 279936]... satisfies z²=5z-6? False

  5^n does NOT satisfy z²=5z-6. It satisfies z=5z-0? No.
  5^n satisfies a(n)=5·a(n-1), a 1st-order recurrence.
  6^n satisfies a(n)=6·a(n-1).

  I(x) = 1 + α₁·x + α₂·x² + α₃·x³ + ...
  Fixing α₂,α₃,..., I(x) is LINEAR in α₁.
  So I(2) and I(3) are linear in α₁:
    I(2) = (1+4α₂+8α₃+...) + 2α₁
    I(3) = (1+9α₂+27α₃+...) + 3α₁

  The RATIO I(3)/I(2) approaches 3/2 as α₁ → ∞
  because the linear terms dominate: 3α₁/(2α₁) = 3/2

