======================================================================
PART 3: WEIGHTED k-NACCI AND THE KEY 3
======================================================================

  WEIGHTED k-NACCI: a(n) = 2·a(n-1) + 2·a(n-2) + ... + 2·a(n-k)
  Wait, what weight gives 3?

  Consider: a(n) = c·[a(n-1) + a(n-2) + ... + a(n-k)]
  The ratio r satisfies r^k = c·(r^{k-1} + ... + r + 1) = c·(r^k-1)/(r-1)
  So r^k(r-1) = c(r^k-1)
  As k→∞: r→c+1 (since r^k dominates)

  c=1: standard k-nacci, ratio → 2 = 1+1
  c=2: weighted k-nacci, ratio → 3 = 2+1
  c=m: ratio → m+1

  The KEY 2 is (1+1)-nacci, the KEY 3 is (2+1)-nacci!

  k= 2: ratio = 2.7320508076, |ratio-3| = 2.68e-01, (2/3)^k = 4.44e-01, err/(2/3)^k = 0.6029
