PART 9: THE 5-6 PATTERN IN TOURNAMENT SPECTRA
======================================================================

  H spectrum pattern:
    n=3: [1, 3]
         diffs: [2]
    n=4: [1, 3, 5]
         diffs: [2, 2]
    n=5: [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15]
         diffs: [2, 2, 4, 2, 2, 2]
    n=6: [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33, 37, 41, 43, 45]
         diffs: [2, 2, 4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 4, 2, 2]

  n=5 diffs: [2,2,4,2,2,2] — gaps of 2 and 4
  n=6 diffs: more complex, but...

  At n=5: H mod 5 values:
    H ≡ 0 (mod 5): [5, 15]
    H ≡ 1 (mod 5): [1, 11]
    H ≡ 3 (mod 5): [3, 13]
    H ≡ 4 (mod 5): [9]

  At n=5: H mod 6 values:
    H ≡ 1 (mod 6): [1, 13]
    H ≡ 3 (mod 6): [3, 9, 15]
    H ≡ 5 (mod 6): [5, 11]

  PATTERN: H mod 6 only takes values {1, 3, 5} at n=5 — always ODD mod 6.
  Because H is always odd (Rédei) and H mod 3 alternates: 1,0,2,0,2,1,0

======================================================================
PART 10: ALTERNATING SUM NON-NEGATIVITY AND KRUSKAL-KATONA
======================================================================

  The claim: α₁ - α₂ + α₃ - ... ≥ 0 for ALL tournaments.
  Equivalently: I(-1) ≤ 1.

  This is a constraint on the f-vector of the independence complex
  of the conflict graph CG(T).

  The Kruskal-Katona theorem constrains f-vectors of simplicial complexes.
  But α₁ ≥ α₂ is STRONGER than what KK gives in general.

  WHY should α₁ ≥ α₂ hold for TOURNAMENT conflict graphs?
  Not all graphs G have this property!

  KEY STRUCTURAL PROPERTY of CG(T):
  All odd cycles through vertex v form a CLIQUE in CG(T).
  (Because any two cycles sharing v share a vertex.)

  This means: the NEIGHBORHOOD of every vertex in CG(T)
  contains a large clique (all cycles through any shared vertex).

  CONSEQUENCE: The independence number is bounded.
  An independent set in CG(T) can contain at most ONE cycle
  through any given vertex v.

  With n vertices in the tournament, an independent set of k
  disjoint cycles uses at least 3k vertices (each cycle has ≥3 vertices).
  So α_k = 0 for k > ⌊n/3⌋.

  More precisely: a set of k disjoint odd cycles uses
  at least 3k vertices (if all are 3-cycles) and at most n vertices.
  So k ≤ ⌊n/3⌋.

  WHY α₁ ≥ α₂:
  Each disjoint PAIR {C₁, C₂} contributes to α₂.
  But C₁ and C₂ individually contribute to α₁.
  So α₂ ≤ C(α₁, 2) trivially.
  But we need the stronger α₁ ≥ α₂.

  CLAIM: In any graph G where every vertex has a neighborhood
  containing a large clique, α₁(G) ≥ α₂(G).
  (Not obvious — this is specific to tournament CGs.)

  VERIFICATION at n=6:
    Checked 32768 tournaments
    α₂ > α₁ violations: 0
    Max ratio α₂/α₁: 0.5000

======================================================================
PART 11: THE RECURRENCE VIEW OF EVERYTHING
======================================================================

  THESIS: Every key quantity in tournament theory satisfies
  a recurrence with characteristic polynomial (z-2)(z-3) = z²-5z+6.

  1. H(T) = I(2) = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ + 8α₃ + ...
     View as: H = Σ 2^k α_k (evaluation at z=2)

  2. I(3) = 1 + 3α₁ + 9α₂ + 27α₃ + ...
     View as: I(3) = Σ 3^k α_k (evaluation at z=3)

  3. For FIXED α-sequence, the function f(x) = Σ x^k α_k satisfies:
     f(x) at x=2: H
     f(x) at x=3: I(3)
     The RATIO f(3)/f(2) → 3/2 generically

  4. The DIFFERENCE I(3) - I(2) = α₁ + 5α₂ + 19α₃ + ...
     = Σ (3^k - 2^k) α_k
     3^k - 2^k satisfies the SAME recurrence z²=5z-6!

  5. The SUM I(3) + I(2) = 2 + 5α₁ + 13α₂ + 35α₃ + ...
     = 2 + Σ (3^k + 2^k) α_k
     3^k + 2^k ALSO satisfies z²=5z-6!

  Verification that 3^k+2^k satisfies a(n)=5a(n-1)-6a(n-2):
    Sequence: [2, 5, 13, 35, 97, 275, 793, 2315, 6817, 20195]
    a(2) = 13, 5a(1)-6a(0) = 13, match: True
    a(3) = 35, 5a(2)-6a(1) = 35, match: True
    a(4) = 97, 5a(3)-6a(2) = 97, match: True
    a(5) = 275, 5a(4)-6a(3) = 275, match: True
    a(6) = 793, 5a(5)-6a(4) = 793, match: True
    a(7) = 2315, 5a(6)-6a(5) = 2315, match: True

  EVERY linear combination A·2^k + B·3^k satisfies z²=5z-6.
  So EVERY evaluation I(x) is connected to I(2) and I(3) via this recurrence.

  Does I(x) satisfy a recurrence in x?
  I(x) = 1 + α₁x + α₂x² is a POLYNOMIAL, not a recurrence.
  But the COEFFICIENTS {1, α₁, α₂, ...} can be viewed as
  the Hadamard product of {1, α₁, α₂, ...} with {1, x, x², ...}

  The generating function Σ α_k z^k has radius of convergence
  related to the max eigenvalue of CG(T).

======================================================================
PART 12: THE TRINITY — 2, 3, AND ∞
======================================================================

  THREE REGIMES OF THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL:

  I(-1) ← TOPOLOGY    (Euler characteristic, Dehn invariant)
  I(1)  ← COUNTING    (total independent sets)
  I(2)  ← GEOMETRY    (Hamiltonian paths, volume)
  I(3)  ← TERNARY     (3-colorings of independent sets)
  I(∞)  ← ASYMPTOTICS (independence number)

  The key RATIOS:
    I(2)/I(1) = H/(1+α₁+α₂+...) ← 'binary amplification'
    I(3)/I(2) = I(3)/H ← 'ternary/binary ratio → 3/2'
    I(2)/I(-1) = H/(1-α₁+α₂-...) ← 'volume/topology ratio'

  Ratios at n=5 (α₂=0):
     H   α₁ I(-1) I(1) I(2) I(3)   I2/I1   I3/I2
     1    0     1    1    1    1  1.0000  1.0000
     3    1     0    2    3    4  1.5000  1.3333
     5    2    -1    3    5    7  1.6667  1.4000
     9    4    -3    5    9   13  1.8000  1.4444
    11    5    -4    6   11   16  1.8333  1.4545
    13    6    -5    7   13   19  1.8571  1.4615
    15    7    -6    8   15   22  1.8750  1.4667

  I(2)/I(1) → 2 as α₁ → ∞ (binary amplification → factor of 2)
  I(3)/I(2) → 3/2 as α₁ → ∞ (ternary vs binary → 50% more)
  These limits are the KEYS: 2 and 3/2 = 3/2.

======================================================================
PART 13: SIMPLEX PACKING AND NON-NEGATIVITY — THE DEEP WHY
======================================================================

  WHY is I(-1) ≤ 1 for tournament conflict graphs?

  SIMPLEX PACKING ARGUMENT:
  O(T) = union of H simplices Δ_σ, one per Hamiltonian path σ.
  These simplices form a TRIANGULATION of O(T).
  The Euler characteristic of a triangulated polytope is 1
  (convex polytope ≅ ball, χ(ball) = 1).

  BUT: χ(O(T)) = 1 is about the POLYTOPE, not the independence complex.
  The independence complex Δ(CG(T)) has χ(Δ) = I(-1).

  Are they related? YES, via the NERVE THEOREM:
  If the H simplices {Δ_σ} cover O(T) and all intersections are
  contractible, then χ(O(T)) = χ(nerve of {Δ_σ}).

  The nerve of {Δ_σ} is the simplicial complex whose vertices
  are the H Hamiltonian paths, and whose faces are sets of
  paths with non-empty common intersection.

  But the independence complex is about the CYCLE STRUCTURE,
  not the path structure. The connection is more subtle.

  TOPOLOGICAL ARGUMENT (sketch):
  The conflict graph CG(T) has chromatic number ≤ n-2
  (since the max independent set uses ≤ ⌊n/3⌋ cycles,
  and the total number of cycles is bounded).
  By Kruskal-Katona + chromatic number bounds,
  the alternating sum α₁-α₂+... is controlled.

  DEEPER: The independence complex of CG(T) might be
  SHELLABLE (admits a shelling order), which would imply
  the h-vector is non-negative, and in particular χ ≤ 1.

  The independence complex at n=5:
  CG(T) has α₁ vertices and α₂ edges.
  Since α₂=0 at n=5, the independence complex is
  a disjoint union of α₁ points (0-dimensional).
  Its Euler characteristic is α₁ (number of components).
  Wait: χ(α₁ points) = α₁. But I(-1) = 1 - α₁.
  Hmm, that's the REDUCED Euler char: χ̃ = χ - 1 = α₁ - 1.
  And I(-1) = 1 + χ̃ = χ. No wait...

  Let me be careful:
  Independence complex Δ = {S ⊆ V(CG): S is independent}
  This includes the EMPTY SET as a face.
  f_{-1} = 1 (empty face), f_0 = α₁ (vertices), f_1 = α₂ (edges), ...
  χ(Δ) = f_{-1} - f_0 + f_1 - ... = 1 - α₁ + α₂ - ... = I(-1)

  So I(-1) = χ(Δ) (Euler characteristic of independence complex).
  For a contractible complex: χ = 1.
  I(-1) ≤ 1 means χ(Δ) ≤ 1.

  At n=5: Δ = {∅} ∪ {{c}: c ∈ cycles} (since α₂=0)
  This is a discrete set of α₁ points plus the empty face.
  χ = 1 - α₁. So I(-1) = 1 - α₁ ∈ {1, 0, -1, -3, -4, -5, -6}

  At n=6: Δ has edges too (disjoint pairs = α₂).
  χ = 1 - α₁ + α₂.

======================================================================
PART 14: THE 2-3 BRIDGE VIA BERNOULLI NUMBERS
======================================================================

  The Bernoulli numbers B_n satisfy:
    Σ B_n x^n/n! = x/(e^x - 1)

  At x=1: Σ B_n/n! = 1/(e-1)
  At x=log2: involves powers of 2
  At x=log3: involves powers of 3

  The Euler numbers E_n (not Bernoulli) satisfy:
    Σ E_n x^n/n! = 1/cosh(x) = 2/(e^x + e^{-x})

  Alternating permutations are counted by Euler numbers.
  TANGENT NUMBERS = E_{2n+1} (odd-index Euler numbers)

  CONNECTION: The deformed Eulerian numbers a_k(T) = A(n,k) + correction.
  The correction depends on the independence polynomial!
  So the 2-3 recurrence acts on the CORRECTION to the Eulerian distribution.

  Eulerian numbers A(5,k) for k=0..4:
    A(5,k) = [1, 26, 66, 26, 1]
    Sum = 120 = 5! = 120

  For a tournament T with α₁ odd cycles:
    a_k(T) = A(5,k) + correction_k
    The corrections sum to 0 (total is always n!)
    The corrections are controlled by α₁


======================================================================
DONE — Keys to the Universe Summary
======================================================================

  2 and 3 are the roots of z² - 5z + 6 = 0
  5 = 2+3 (sum, first non-trivial n)
  6 = 2·3 (product, first α₂ appears)
  7 = 2²+3 = Φ₃(2) (forbidden H value)
  8 = 2³ (weight of triple cycles in I(2))
  10 = NOT a cyclotomic value (even = impossible)
  11 = Φ₁₀(2) (period 10 = 2·5)

  k-nacci → 2 at rate (1/2)^k
  weighted(2) k-nacci → 3 at rate (2/3)^k
  Convergence rates are key/key: 1/2 and 2/3

  I(-1) = Euler characteristic ≤ 1 (topology)
  I(1) = total independent sets (counting)
  I(2) = H = Hamiltonian paths (geometry)
  I(3) = ternary evaluation (the other key)

  Alternating sum non-negativity ⟺ α₁ ≥ α₂
  ⟺ simplex dominance in independence complex
  ⟺ tournament polytope has bounded topological complexity

